item.description:
Postman's collection JSON format cannot export/import a WebSocket request (confirmed platform limitation: https://github.com/postmanlabs/postman-app-support/issues/11252) — that's why this folder has no runnable request in it. To connect manually:

0. In Postman: File > New > WebSocket Request. Paste the URL: {{wsBaseUrl}}/hubs/aircraft (this collection's wsBaseUrl variable is ws://localhost:5273 by default).

SignalR layers its own JSON-Hub-Protocol handshake and invocation framing on top of the raw WebSocket connection — Postman does not speak this automatically, so send these messages yourself in order once connected:

1. Handshake (required first, before anything else works) — send exactly:
   {"protocol":"json","version":1}
   (the trailing character is the ASCII Record Separator, 0x1E — every SignalR JSON-protocol message, in both directions, ends with it). Expect the server to reply with an empty handshake response: {}

2. Subscribe to a bounding box — reuses this collection's lamin/lomin/lamax/lomax variables:
   {"type":1,"invocationId":"1","target":"Subscribe","arguments":[{{lamin}},{{lomin}},{{lamax}},{{lomax}}]}
   Expect a completion message echoing invocationId "1" with the initial AircraftSnapshot as its result: {"type":3,"invocationId":"1","result":{"aircraft":[...],"stale":false}}

3. From here, the server pushes AircraftUpdate messages on its own broadcast interval (see api/README.md) for as long as this connection stays open and its bounding box remains registered:
   {"type":1,"target":"AircraftUpdate","arguments":[{"aircraft":[...],"stale":false}]}

No further client message is required after Subscribe — closing the WebSocket connection is enough to unregister this bounding box server-side.
